body:
This is a large-scale refactor around `LayerLifecycle`. First off, `LayerLifecycle` has been renamed to `Layer` to make clear that it's the first-class construct to deal with layers in libcnb. The API design is similar to the new `Buildpack` trait introduced by #129 and integrates nicely with it. Compared to previously, `Layer` does not need to pass around explicit values, for example, for the buildpack metadata type, it gets that value from the associated `Buildpack` type.

In the same vein, the low-level layer methods on `BuildContext` have been removed. They were very hard to use correctly due to the complexity of the CNB spec. I believe all use-cases can be implemented with the `Layer` trait. However, should we notice we need to provide low-level helpers, we can bring them back in a more organised way (probably in a low-level crate similar to `libcnb-data`).

In addition, this PR fulfils the promise of #30 to integrate `LayerEnv` more deeply into the framework. The `create` and `update` methods on `Layer` now return (via `LayerResult`) a `LayerEnv` value which will be automatically written to disk by libcnb which also handles any errors during that process. When a layer is run/handled, the resulting value will be a `LayerData` struct that contains in instance of `LayerEnv` that allows the buildpack to easily work the environment provided by that layer and can pass it to subsequent layers. This includes implicit environment variables such as `<layer_dir>/bin` being automatically added to `PATH` if present. See the Ruby example how the Ruby environment is passed from the `ruby` layer to the `bundler` layer with almost zero effort.

The changes in this PR are much more thoroughly tested and documented compared to `LayerLifecycle`. Testing can still be improved and I plan to add more high-level/integration tests for `BuildContext::handle_layer` in a separate PR (we need some other changes to make the implementation of those tests easier). Those tests are tracked in #161.

Last but not least, this PR makes `Layer` compatible with version `0.6` of the CNB spec. This fixes #103.

